# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: electrodynamics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] The physical phenomena that electromagnetism describes have been studied as separate fields since antiquity.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] For example, there were many advances in the field of optics centuries before light was understood to be an electromagnetic wave.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] However, the theory of electromagnetism, as it is currently understood, grew out of Michael Faraday's experiments suggesting the existence of an electromagnetic field and James Clerk Maxwell's use of differential equations to describe it in his *A Treatise on Electricity and Magnetism* (1873).
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] The development of electromagnetism in Europe included the development of methods to measure voltage, current, capacitance, and resistance.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] Detailed historical accounts are given by Wolfgang Pauli, E.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] where all boldfaced quantities are vectors: **F** is the force that a particle with charge *q* experiences, **E** is the electric field at the location of the particle, **v** is the velocity of the particle, **B** is the magnetic field at the location of the particle.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] The above equation illustrates that the Lorentz force is the sum of two vectors.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] One is the cross product of the velocity and magnetic field vectors.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] Based on the properties of the cross product, this produces a vector that is perpendicular to both the velocity and magnetic field vectors.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] The other vector is in the same direction as the electric field.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] The sum of these two vectors is the Lorentz force.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] where *q*0 is what is known as a test charge and **F** is the force on that charge.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] The size of the charge does not really matter, as long as it is small enough not to influence the electric field by its mere presence.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] What is plain from this definition, though, is that the unit of **E** is N/C (newtons per coulomb).
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] This unit is equal to V/m (volts per meter); see below.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] In electrostatics, where charges are not moving, around a distribution of point charges, the forces determined from Coulomb's law may be summed.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] where *n* is the number of charges, *qi* is the amount of charge associated with the *i*th charge, **r***i* is the position of the *i*th charge, **r** is the position where the electric field is being determined, and *ε*0 is the electric constant.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] where $\rho (\mathbf {r'} )$ is the charge density and $\mathbf {r} -\mathbf {r'}$ is the vector that points from the volume element $\mathrm {d^{3}} \mathbf {r'}$ to the point in space where **E** is being determined.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] Both of the above equations are cumbersome, especially if one wants to determine **E** as a function of position.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] A scalar function called the electric potential can help.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] where $\varphi ({\textbf {r}})$ is the electric potential, and *C* is the path over which the integral is being taken.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] From Maxwell's equations, it is clear that ∇ × **E** is not always zero, and hence the scalar potential alone is insufficient to define the electric field exactly.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] As a result, one must add a correction factor, which is generally done by subtracting the time derivative of the **A** vector potential described below.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] Whenever the charges are quasistatic, however, this condition will be essentially met.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] where *q* is the point charge's charge, **r** is the position at which the potential is being determined, and **r***i* is the position of each point charge.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] where $\rho (\mathbf {r'} )$ is the charge density, and $\mathbf {r} -\mathbf {r'}$ is the distance from the volume element $\mathrm {d^{3}} \mathbf {r'}$ to point in space where *φ* is being determined.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] The scalar *φ* will add to other potentials as a scalar.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] This makes it relatively easy to break complex problems down into simple parts and add their potentials.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] Taking the definition of *φ* backwards, we see that the electric field is just the negative gradient (the del operator) of the potential.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] From this formula it is clear that **E** can be expressed in V/m (volts per meter).
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] A changing electromagnetic field propagates away from its origin in the form of a wave.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] These waves travel in vacuum at the speed of light and exist in a wide spectrum of wavelengths.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] Examples of the dynamic fields of electromagnetic radiation (in order of increasing frequency): radio waves, microwaves, light (infrared, visible light and ultraviolet), x-rays and gamma rays.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] In the field of particle physics this electromagnetic radiation is the manifestation of the electromagnetic interaction between charged particles.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] As simple and satisfying as Coulomb's equation may be, it is not entirely correct in the context of classical electromagnetism.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] Problems arise because changes in charge distributions require a non-zero amount of time to be "felt" elsewhere (required by special relativity).
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] For the fields of general charge distributions, the retarded potentials can be computed and differentiated accordingly to yield Jefimenko's equations.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] Retarded potentials can also be derived for point charges, and the equations are known as the Liénard–Wiechert potentials.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] where q is the point charge's charge and ${\textbf {r}}$ is the position. ${\textbf {r}}_{q}$ and ${\textbf {v}}_{q}$ are the position and velocity of the charge, respectively, as a function of retarded time.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] These can then be differentiated accordingly to obtain the complete field equations for a moving point particle.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] Branches of classical electromagnetism such as optics, electrical and electronic engineering consist of a collection of relevant mathematical models of different degrees of simplification and idealization to enhance the understanding of specific electrodynamics phenomena.
[src:electrodynamics/classical-electromagnetism] An electrodynamics phenomenon is determined by the particular fields, specific densities of electric charges and currents, and the particular transmission medium.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In physics, **electromagnetic radiation** (**EMR**) or an **electromagnetic wave** (**EMW**) is a self-propagating wave of the electromagnetic field that carries momentum and radiant energy through space.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] It encompasses a broad spectrum, classified by frequency (inversely proportional to wavelength), ranging from radio waves, microwaves, infrared, visible light, ultraviolet, X-rays, to gamma rays.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] All forms of EMR travel at the speed of light in a vacuum and exhibit wave–particle duality, behaving both as waves and as discrete particles called photons.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Electromagnetic radiation is produced by accelerating charged particles such as from the Sun and other celestial bodies or artificially generated for various applications.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Its interaction with matter depends on wavelength, influencing its uses in communication, medicine, industry, and scientific research.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Radio waves enable broadcasting and wireless communication, infrared is used in thermal imaging, visible light is essential for vision, and higher-energy radiation, such as X-rays and gamma rays, is applied in medical imaging, cancer treatment, and industrial inspection.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Higher energy EMR, especially in the UV and above, has been associated with negative health effects.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In quantum mechanics, an alternate way of viewing EMR is that it consists of photons, uncharged elementary particles with zero rest mass which are the quanta of the electromagnetic field, responsible for all electromagnetic interactions.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Quantum electrodynamics is the theory of how EMR interacts with matter on an atomic level.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Quantum effects provide additional sources of EMR, such as the transition of electrons to lower energy levels in an atom and black-body radiation.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Maxwell's equations and their solutions (Panofsky–Phillips equations) indicate that a component of the electric field and magnetic field has an amplitude that decreases inversely with the distance between the source and the observer (1/r), allowing it to be detectable at large distances.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] These components are transverse to the direction of propagation (**n**) of the radiation.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] One has $\mathbf {E} \perp \mathbf {B} \perp \mathbf {n}$ , with **E** and **B** related by: $\mathbf {B} ={\frac {\mathbf {n} \times \mathbf {E} }{c}}$ Note also that these fields propagate through space at the speed of light, i.e. at 299,792,458 m/s.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Electromagnetic radiation is produced by accelerating charged particles and can be naturally emitted, as from the Sun and other celestial bodies, or artificially generated for various applications.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The energy in electromagnetic waves is sometimes called radiant energy.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The electromagnetic waves' energy does not need a propagating medium to travel through space; they move through a vacuum at the speed of light.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Electric and magnetic fields obey the properties of superposition.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Thus, a field due to any particular particle or time-varying electric or magnetic field contributes to the fields present in the same space due to other causes.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Further, as they are vector fields, all magnetic and electric field vectors add together according to vector addition.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] For example, in optics two or more coherent light waves may interact and by constructive or destructive interference yield a resultant irradiance deviating from the sum of the component irradiances of the individual light waves.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The electromagnetic fields of light are not affected by traveling through static electric or magnetic fields in a linear medium such as a vacuum.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] However, in nonlinear media, such as some crystals, interactions can occur between light and static electric and magnetic fields—these interactions include the Faraday effect and the Kerr effect.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In refraction, a wave crossing from one medium to another of different density alters its speed and direction upon entering the new medium.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The ratio of the refractive indices of the media determines the degree of refraction, and is summarized by Snell's law.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Light of composite wavelengths (natural sunlight) disperses into a visible spectrum passing through a prism, because of the wavelength-dependent refractive index of the prism material (dispersion); that is, each component wave within the composite light is bent a different amount.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] EM radiation exhibits both wave properties and particle properties at the same time (known as wave–particle duality).
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Both wave and particle characteristics have been confirmed in many experiments.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Wave characteristics are more apparent when EM radiation is measured over relatively large timescales and over large distances while particle characteristics are more evident when measuring small timescales and distances.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] For example, when electromagnetic radiation is absorbed by matter, particle-like properties will be more obvious when the average number of photons in the cube of the relevant wavelength is much smaller than 1.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] It is not so difficult to experimentally observe non-uniform deposition of energy when light is absorbed, however this alone is not evidence of "particulate" behavior.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Rather, it reflects the quantum nature of *matter*.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] A quantum theory of the interaction between electromagnetic radiation and matter such as electrons is described by the theory of quantum electrodynamics.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Electromagnetic waves can be polarized, reflected, refracted, or diffracted, and can interfere with each other.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Some experiments display both the wave and particle natures of electromagnetic waves, such as the self-interference of a single photon.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In homogeneous, isotropic media, electromagnetic radiation is a transverse wave, meaning that its oscillations are perpendicular to the direction of energy transfer and travel.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The electric and magnetic parts of the field in an electromagnetic wave stand in a fixed ratio of strengths to satisfy the two Maxwell's equations that specify how one is produced from the other.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In dissipation-less (lossless) media, these E and B fields are also in phase, with both reaching maxima and minima at the same points in space.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In the far-field EM radiation which is described by the two source-free Maxwell curl operator equations, a time-change in one type of field is proportional to the curl of the other.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] These derivatives require that the E and B fields in EMR are in phase.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] An important aspect of light's nature is its frequency.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The frequency of a wave is its rate of oscillation and is measured in hertz, the SI unit of frequency, where one hertz is equal to one oscillation per second.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Light usually has multiple frequencies that sum to form the resultant wave.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Different frequencies undergo different angles of refraction, a phenomenon known as dispersion.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] A monochromatic wave (a wave of a single frequency) consists of successive troughs and crests, and the distance between two adjacent crests or troughs is called the wavelength.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Waves of the electromagnetic spectrum vary in size, from very long radio waves longer than a continent to very short gamma rays smaller than atom nuclei.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] where *v* is the speed of the wave (*c* in a vacuum or less in other media), *f* is the frequency, and *λ* is the wavelength.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] As waves cross boundaries between different media, their speeds change but their frequencies remain constant.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Electromagnetic waves in free space must be solutions of Maxwell's electromagnetic wave equation.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Two main classes of solutions are known, namely plane waves and spherical waves.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The plane waves may be viewed as the limiting case of spherical waves at a very large (ideally infinite) distance from the source.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Both types of waves can have a waveform which is an arbitrary time function (so long as it is sufficiently differentiable to conform to the wave equation).
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] As with any time function, this can be decomposed by means of Fourier analysis into its frequency spectrum, or individual sinusoidal components, each of which contains a single frequency, amplitude, and phase.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Such a component wave is said to be *monochromatic*.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Interference is the superposition of two or more waves resulting in a new wave pattern.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] If the fields have components in the same direction, they constructively interfere, while opposite directions cause destructive interference.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Additionally, multiple polarization signals can be combined (i.e. interfered) to form new states of polarization, which is known as parallel polarization state generation.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] James Clerk Maxwell derived a wave form of the electric and magnetic equations, thus uncovering the wave-like nature of electric and magnetic fields and their symmetry.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Because the speed of EM waves predicted by the wave equation coincided with the measured speed of light, Maxwell concluded that light itself is an EM wave.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Maxwell's equations were confirmed by Heinrich Hertz through experiments with radio waves.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Out of the four equations, two of the equations that Maxwell refined were Faraday's Law of Induction and Ampère's circuital law, which he extended by adding the displacement current term to the equations himself.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Maxwell thought that the displacement current, which he viewed as the motion of bound charges, gave rise to the magnetic field.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The other two equations are Gauss's law and Gauss's law for magnetism.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Maxwell's equations established that some charges and currents (*sources*) produce local electromagnetic fields near them that do not radiate.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Currents directly produce magnetic fields of a magnetic-dipole–type that die out with distance from the current.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In a similar manner, moving charges pushed apart in a conductor by a changing electrical potential (such as in an antenna) produce an electric-dipole–type electrical field, but this also declines with distance.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Neither of these behaviours is responsible for EM radiation.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Instead, they only efficiently transfer energy to a receiver very close to the source, such as inside a transformer.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The near field has strong effects on its source, with any energy withdrawn by a receiver causing increased *load* (decreased electrical reactance) on the source.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The near field does not propagate freely into space, carrying energy away without a distance limit, but rather oscillates, returning its energy to the transmitter if it is not absorbed by a receiver.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] This far part of the electromagnetic field *is* electromagnetic radiation.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The far fields propagate (radiate) without allowing the transmitter to affect them.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] This causes them to be independent in the sense that their existence and their energy, after they have left the transmitter, is completely independent of both transmitter and receiver.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Due to conservation of energy, the amount of power passing through any closed surface drawn around the source is the same.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The power density of EM radiation from an isotropic source decreases with the inverse square of the distance from the source; this is called the inverse-square law.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Field intensity due to dipole parts of the near field varies according to an inverse-cube law, and thus fades with distance.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The distinction between near field and radiated field is illustrated by the Panofsky–Phillips equations, which give the general expression of the electric and magnetic fields produced by an arbitrary distribution of charges and currents.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The terms of the Panofsky–Phillips equations can be separated into two categories: The "near field" terms have a **$1/r^{2}$** dependence, and are significant only in the immediate vicinity of the sources.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The "far field" terms have a **$1/r$** dependence.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Due to their slower decrease with distance, they dominate as one moves away from the sources.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] By contrast, the term associated with the changing static electric field of the particle and the magnetic term that results from the particle's uniform velocity are both associated with the near field, and do not comprise electromagnetic radiation.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] An anomaly arose in the late 19th century involving a contradiction between the wave theory of light and measurements of the electromagnetic spectra that were being emitted by thermal radiators known as black bodies.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Physicists struggled with this problem unsuccessfully for many years, and it later became known as the ultraviolet catastrophe.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In 1900, Max Planck developed a new theory of black-body radiation that explained the observed spectrum.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Planck's theory was based on the idea that black bodies emit light (and other electromagnetic radiation) only as discrete bundles or packets of energy.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In 1905, Albert Einstein proposed that light quanta be regarded as real particles.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Later the particle of light was given the name photon, to correspond with other particles being described around this time, such as the electron and proton.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] where *h* is the Planck constant, $\lambda$ is the wavelength and *c* is the speed of light.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] This is sometimes known as the Planck–Einstein equation.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In quantum theory (see first quantization) the energy of the photons is thus directly proportional to the frequency of the EMR wave.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Experimental measurements demonstrated that the energy of individual ejected electrons was proportional to the *frequency*, rather than the *intensity*, of the light.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Furthermore, below a certain minimum frequency, which depended on the particular metal, no current would flow regardless of the intensity.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] These observations appeared to contradict the wave theory, and for years physicists tried to find an explanation.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In 1905, Einstein explained this phenomenon by resurrecting the particle theory of light.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Because of the preponderance of evidence in favor of the wave theory, however, Einstein's ideas were met initially with great skepticism among established physicists.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Eventually Einstein's explanation was accepted as new particle-like behavior of light was observed, such as the Compton effect.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] As a photon is absorbed by an atom, it excites the atom, elevating an electron to a higher energy level (one that is on average farther from the nucleus).
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] When an electron in an excited molecule or atom descends to a lower energy level, it emits a photon of light at a frequency corresponding to the energy difference.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Since the energy levels of electrons in atoms are discrete, each element and each molecule emits and absorbs its own characteristic frequencies.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Immediate photon emission is called fluorescence, a type of photoluminescence.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] An example is visible light emitted from fluorescent paints, in response to ultraviolet (blacklight).
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Many other fluorescent emissions are known in spectral bands other than visible light.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Delayed emission is called phosphorescence.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Quantum mechanics also governs emission, which is seen when an emitting gas glows due to excitation of the atoms from any mechanism, including heat.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] As electrons descend to lower energy levels, a spectrum is emitted that represents the jumps between the energy levels of the electrons, but lines are seen because again emission happens only at particular energies after excitation.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] An example is the emission spectrum of nebulae.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Rapidly moving electrons are most sharply accelerated when they encounter a region of force, so they are responsible for producing much of the highest frequency electromagnetic radiation observed in nature.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] These phenomena can be used to detect the composition of gases lit from behind (absorption spectra) and for glowing gases (emission spectra).
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Spectroscopy (for example) determines what chemical elements comprise a particular star.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Shifts in the frequency of the spectral lines for an element, called a redshift, can be used to determine the star's cosmological distance.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The modern theory that explains the nature of light includes the notion of wave–particle duality.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The theory is based on the concept that every quantum entity can show wave-like or particle-like behaviors, depending on observation.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The observation led to the collapse of the entity's wave function.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] If it is based on the Copenhagen interpretation, the observation does really collapse the wave function; for the many-worlds interpretation, all possible outcomes of the collapse happened in parallel universes; for the pilot wave theory, the particle behaviour is simply determined by waves.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The duality nature of a real photon has been observed in the double-slit experiment.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Together, wave and particle effects fully explain the emission and absorption spectra of EM radiation.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The matter-composition of the medium through which the light travels determines the nature of the absorption and emission spectrum.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] These bands correspond to the allowed energy levels in the atoms.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Dark bands in the absorption spectrum are due to the atoms in an intervening medium between source and observer.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The atoms absorb certain frequencies of the light between emitter and detector/eye, then emit them in all directions.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] A dark band appears to the detector, due to the radiation scattered out of the light beam.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] For instance, dark bands in the light emitted by a distant star are due to the atoms in the star's atmosphere.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In empty space (vacuum), electromagnetic radiation travels at the speed of light, c , 299,792,458 meters per second (approximately 186,000 miles per second).
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The reason for this is that in matter the electric and magnetic fields of the wave are slowed because they polarize the charged particles in the medium they pass through.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The oscillating electric field causes nearby positive and negative charges in atoms to move slightly apart and together, inducing an oscillating polarization, creating an electric polarization field.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The oscillating magnetic field moves nearby magnetic dipoles, inducing an oscillating magnetization, creating an induced oscillating magnetic field.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] These induced fields, superposed on the original wave fields, slow the wave (Ewald–Oseen extinction theorem).
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The amount of slowing depends on the electromagnetic properties of the medium, the electric permittivity and magnetic permeability.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In the SI system of units, empty space has a vacuum permittivity of $\epsilon _{\text{0}}=$ 8.854×10−12 F/m (farads per meter) and a vacuum permeability of $\mu _{\text{0}}=$ 1.257×10−6 H/m (henries per meter).
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In a medium that is isotropic and linear, which means the electric polarization is proportional to the electric field $\mathbf {D} =\epsilon \mathbf {E}$ and the magnetization is proportional to the magnetic field $\mathbf {H} ={1 \over \mu }\mathbf {B}$ .
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] If the permittivity and permeability of the medium is constant for different frequency EM waves, this is called a *non-dispersive* medium.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In this case all EM wave frequencies would travel at the same velocity, and the waveshape stays constant as it travels.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] However in real matter $\epsilon$ and $\mu$ typically vary with frequency, this is called a *dispersive* medium.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In dispersive media different spectral bands have different propagation characteristics, and an arbitrary wave changes shape as it travels through the medium.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Electromagnetic radiation of wavelengths other than those of visible light were discovered in the early 19th century.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The discovery of infrared radiation is ascribed to astronomer William Herschel, who published his results in 1800 before the Royal Society of London.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Herschel used a glass prism to refract light from the Sun and detected invisible rays that caused heating beyond the red part of the spectrum, through an increase in the temperature recorded with a thermometer.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] These "calorific rays" were later termed infrared.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In 1801 German physicist Johann Wilhelm Ritter discovered ultraviolet in an experiment similar to Herschel's, using sunlight and a glass prism.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Ritter noted that invisible rays near the violet edge of a solar spectrum dispersed by a triangular prism darkened silver chloride preparations more quickly than did the nearby violet light.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Ritter's experiments were an early precursor to what would become photography.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Ritter noted that the ultraviolet rays (which at first were called "chemical rays") were capable of causing chemical reactions.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In 1862–64 James Clerk Maxwell developed equations for the electromagnetic field which suggested that waves in the field would travel with a speed that was very close to the known speed of light.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Maxwell therefore suggested that visible light (as well as invisible infrared and ultraviolet rays by inference) all consisted of propagating disturbances (or radiation) in the electromagnetic field.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Radio waves were first produced deliberately by Heinrich Hertz in 1887, using electrical circuits calculated to produce oscillations at a much lower frequency than that of visible light, following recipes for producing oscillating charges and currents suggested by Maxwell's equations.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Hertz also developed ways to detect these waves, and produced and characterized what were later termed radio waves and microwaves.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Wilhelm Röntgen discovered and named X-rays.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] After experimenting with high voltages applied to an evacuated tube on 8 November 1895, he noticed a fluorescence on a nearby plate of coated glass.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In one month, he discovered X-rays' main properties.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The last portion of the EM spectrum to be discovered was associated with radioactivity.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Henri Becquerel found that uranium salts caused fogging of an unexposed photographic plate through a covering paper in a manner similar to X-rays, and Marie Curie discovered that only certain elements gave off these rays of energy, soon discovering the intense radiation of radium.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The radiation from pitchblende was differentiated into alpha rays (alpha particles) and beta rays (beta particles) by Ernest Rutherford through simple experimentation in 1899, but these proved to be charged particulate types of radiation.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] However, in 1900 the French scientist Paul Villard discovered a third neutrally charged and especially penetrating type of radiation from radium, and after he described it, Rutherford realized it must be yet a third type of radiation, which in 1903 Rutherford named gamma rays.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] EM radiation (the designation 'radiation' excludes static electric and magnetic and near fields) is classified by wavelength into radio, microwave, infrared, visible, ultraviolet, X-rays, and gamma rays.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Arbitrary electromagnetic waves can be expressed by Fourier analysis in terms of sinusoidal waves (monochromatic radiation), which in turn can each be classified into these regions of the EMR spectrum.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] For certain classes of EM waves, the waveform is most usefully treated as *random*, and then spectral analysis must be done by slightly different mathematical techniques appropriate to random or stochastic processes.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In such cases, the individual frequency components are represented in terms of their *power* content, and the phase information is not preserved.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Such a representation is called the power spectral density of the random process.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Random electromagnetic radiation requiring this kind of analysis is, for example, encountered in the interior of stars, and in certain other very wideband forms of radiation such as the zero-point wave field of the electromagnetic vacuum.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The behavior of EM radiation and its interaction with matter depends on its frequency, and changes qualitatively as the frequency changes.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Lower frequencies have longer wavelengths, and higher frequencies have shorter wavelengths, and are associated with photons of higher energy.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] There is no fundamental limit known to these wavelengths or energies, at either end of the spectrum, although photons with energies near the Planck energy or exceeding it (far too high to have ever been observed) will require new physical theories to describe.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Electromagnetic radiation phenomena with wavelengths ranging from one meter to one millimeter are called microwaves; with frequencies between 300 MHz (0.3 GHz) and 300 GHz.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] When radio waves impinge upon a conductor, they couple to the conductor, travel along it, and induce an electric current on the conductor surface by moving the electrons of the conducting material in correlated bunches of charge.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] At radio and microwave frequencies, EMR interacts with matter largely as a bulk collection of charges which are spread out over large numbers of affected atoms.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In electrical conductors, such induced bulk movement of charges (electric currents) results in absorption of the EMR, or else separations of charges that cause generation of new EMR (effective reflection of the EMR).
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] An example is absorption or emission of radio waves by antennas, or absorption of microwaves by water or other molecules with an electric dipole moment, as for example inside a microwave oven.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] These interactions produce either electric currents or heat, or both.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Like radio and microwave, infrared (IR) is reflected by metals (and also most EMR, well into the ultraviolet range).
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] However, unlike lower-frequency radio and microwave radiation, infrared EMR commonly interacts with dipoles present in single molecules, which change as atoms vibrate at the ends of a single chemical bond.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] It is consequently absorbed by a wide range of substances, causing them to increase in temperature as the vibrations dissipate as heat.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The same process, run in reverse, causes bulk substances to radiate in the infrared spontaneously (see thermal radiation section below).
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Infrared radiation is divided into spectral subregions.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] While different subdivision schemes exist, the spectrum is commonly divided as near-infrared (0.75–1.4 μm), short-wavelength infrared (1.4–3 μm), mid-wavelength infrared (3–8 μm), long-wavelength infrared (8–15 μm) and far infrared (15–1000 μm).
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Some animals, such as snakes, have thermo-sensitive membranes (pit organs) that can detect temperature differences, allowing them to sense infrared radiation.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Natural sources produce EM radiation across the spectrum.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] EM radiation with a wavelength between approximately 400 nm and 700 nm is directly detected by the human eye and perceived as visible light.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Other wavelengths, especially nearby infrared (longer than 700 nm) and ultraviolet (shorter than 400 nm) are also sometimes referred to as light.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] As frequency increases into the visible range, photons have enough energy to change the bond structure of some individual molecules.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] It is not a coincidence that this happens in the visible range, as the mechanism of vision involves the change in bonding of a single molecule, retinal, which absorbs a single photon.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The change in retinal causes a change in the shape of the rhodopsin protein it is contained in, which starts the biochemical process that causes the retina of the human eye to sense the light.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Visible light is able to affect only a tiny percentage of all molecules.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Usually not in a permanent or damaging way, rather the photon excites an electron which then emits another photon when returning to its original position.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] This is the source of color produced by most dyes.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] When a photon is absorbed, the retinal permanently changes structure from cis to trans, and requires a protein to convert it back, i.e. reset it to be able to function as a light detector again.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Photosynthesis becomes possible in this range as well, for the same reason.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] A single molecule of chlorophyll is excited by a single photon.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In plant tissues that conduct photosynthesis, carotenoids act to quench electronically excited chlorophyll produced by visible light in a process called non-photochemical quenching, to prevent reactions that would otherwise interfere with photosynthesis at high light levels.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Limited evidence indicate that some reactive oxygen species are created by visible light in skin, and that these may have some role in photoaging, in the same manner as ultraviolet A.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Infrared, microwaves, and radio waves are known to damage molecules and biological tissue only by bulk heating, not excitation from single photons of the radiation.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] As frequency increases into the ultraviolet, photons now carry enough energy (about three electron volts or more) to excite certain doubly bonded molecules into permanent chemical rearrangement.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] DNA is also indirectly damaged by reactive oxygen species produced by ultraviolet A (UVA), which has energy too low to damage DNA directly.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] This is why ultraviolet at all wavelengths can damage DNA, and is capable of causing cancer, and (for UVB) skin burns (sunburn) that are far worse than would be produced by simple heating (temperature increase) effects.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] At the higher end of the ultraviolet range, the energy of photons becomes large enough to impart enough energy to electrons to cause them to be liberated from the atom, in a process called photoionisation.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The energy required for this is always larger than about 10 electron volt (eV) corresponding with wavelengths smaller than 124 nm (some sources suggest a more realistic cutoff of 33 eV, which is the energy required to ionize water).
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] This high end of the ultraviolet spectrum with energies in the approximate ionization range, is sometimes called "extreme UV".
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Ionizing UV is strongly filtered by the Earth's atmosphere.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Electromagnetic radiation composed of photons that carry minimum-ionization energy, or more (which includes the entire spectrum with shorter wavelengths), is therefore termed ionizing radiation.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] (Many other kinds of ionizing radiation are made of non-EM particles.) Electromagnetic-type ionizing radiation extends from the extreme ultraviolet to all higher frequencies and shorter wavelengths, which means that all X-rays and gamma rays qualify.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] These are capable of the most severe types of molecular damage, which can happen in biology to any type of biomolecule, including mutation and cancer, and often at great depths below the skin, since the higher end of the X-ray spectrum, and all of the gamma ray spectrum, penetrate matter.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Most UV and X-rays are blocked by absorption first from molecular nitrogen, and then (for wavelengths in the upper UV) from the electronic excitation of dioxygen and finally ozone at the mid-range of UV.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Only 30% of the Sun's ultraviolet light reaches the ground, and almost all of this is well transmitted.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Visible light is well transmitted in air, a property known as an atmospheric window, as it is not energetic enough to excite nitrogen, oxygen, or ozone, but too energetic to excite molecular vibrational frequencies of water vapor and carbon dioxide.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Absorption bands in the infrared are due to modes of vibrational excitation in water vapor.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] However, at energies too low to excite water vapor, the atmosphere becomes transparent again, allowing free transmission of most microwave and radio waves.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Finally, at radio wavelengths longer than 10 m or so (about 30 MHz), the air in the lower atmosphere remains transparent to radio, but plasma in certain layers of the ionosphere begins to interact with radio waves (see skywave).
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] This property allows some longer wavelengths (100 m or 3 MHz) to be reflected and results in shortwave radio beyond line-of-sight.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] However, certain ionospheric effects begin to block incoming radiowaves from space, when their frequency is less than about 10 MHz (wavelength longer than about 30 m).
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The basic structure of matter involves charged particles bound together.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] When electromagnetic radiation impinges on matter, it causes the charged particles to oscillate and gain energy.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The ultimate fate of this energy depends on the context.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] It could be immediately re-radiated and appear as scattered, reflected, or transmitted radiation.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] It may get dissipated into other microscopic motions within the matter, coming to thermal equilibrium and manifesting itself as thermal energy, or even kinetic energy, in the material.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] This happens for infrared, microwave, and radio wave radiation.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Intense radio waves can thermally burn living tissue and can cook food.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] In addition to infrared lasers, sufficiently intense visible and ultraviolet lasers can easily set paper afire.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Ionizing radiation creates high-speed electrons in a material and breaks chemical bonds, but after these electrons collide many times with other atoms eventually most of the energy becomes thermal energy all in a tiny fraction of a second.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] This caveat also applies to UV, even though almost all of it is not ionizing, because UV can damage molecules due to electronic excitation, which is far greater per unit energy than heating effects.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Infrared radiation in the spectral distribution of a black body is usually considered a form of heat, since it has an equivalent temperature and is associated with an entropy change per unit of thermal energy.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] However, "heat" is a technical term in physics and thermodynamics and is often confused with thermal energy.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Any type of electromagnetic energy can be transformed into thermal energy in interaction with matter.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Thus, *any* electromagnetic radiation can "heat" (in the sense of increase the thermal energy temperature of) a material, when it is absorbed.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The inverse or time-reversed process of absorption is thermal radiation.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Much of the thermal energy in matter consists of random motion of charged particles, and this energy can be radiated away from the matter.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The resulting radiation may subsequently be absorbed by another piece of matter, with the deposited energy heating the material.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The electromagnetic radiation in an opaque cavity at thermal equilibrium is effectively a form of thermal energy, having maximum radiation entropy.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Bioelectromagnetics is the study of the interactions and effects of EM radiation on living organisms.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The effects of electromagnetic radiation upon living cells, including those in humans, depends upon the radiation's power and frequency.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] For low-frequency radiation (radio waves to near ultraviolet) the best-understood effects are those due to radiation power alone, acting through heating when radiation is absorbed.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] For these thermal effects, frequency is important as it affects the intensity of the radiation and penetration into the organism (for example, microwaves penetrate better than infrared).
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] It is widely accepted that low frequency fields that are too weak to cause significant heating could not possibly have any biological effect.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Some research suggests that weaker *non-thermal* electromagnetic fields (including weak ELF magnetic fields, although the latter does not strictly qualify as EM radiation) and modulated RF and microwave fields can have biological effects, though the significance of this is unclear.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] All UV frequencies have been classed as Group 1 carcinogens by the World Health Organization.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Ultraviolet radiation from sun exposure is the primary cause of skin cancer, the most common type of cancer among fair-skinned people.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] UV radiation damages DNA and cells as well as causing mutations that block DNA repair.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] Visible and infrared light may increase photoaging, but sunscreens do not generally protect against these effects.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The World Health Organization has classified radio frequency electromagnetic radiation as Group 2B—possibly carcinogenic.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] This group contains possible carcinogens such as lead, coffee, and automobile exhaust.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] The heat ray is an application of EMR that makes use of microwave frequencies to create an unpleasant heating effect in the upper layer of the skin.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] A publicly known heat ray weapon called the Active Denial System was developed by the US military as an experimental weapon to deny the enemy access to an area.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] A death ray is a theoretical weapon that delivers heat ray based on electromagnetic energy at levels that are capable of injuring human tissue.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p01] An inventor of a death ray, Harry Grindell Matthews, claimed to have lost sight in his left eye while working on his death ray weapon based on a microwave magnetron from the 1920s (a normal microwave oven creates a tissue damaging cooking effect inside the oven at around 2 kV/m).
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] Electromagnetic waves are predicted by the classical laws of electricity and magnetism, known as Maxwell's equations.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] There are nontrivial solutions of the homogeneous Maxwell's equations (without charges or currents), describing *waves* of changing electric and magnetic fields.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] Thus Maxwell's equations connect the vacuum permittivity $\varepsilon _{0}$ , the vacuum permeability $\mu _{0}$ , and the speed of light, *c*0, via the above equation.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] This relationship had been discovered by Wilhelm Eduard Weber and Rudolf Kohlrausch prior to the development of Maxwell's electrodynamics, however Maxwell was the first to produce a field theory consistent with waves traveling at the speed of light.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] These are only two equations versus the original four, so more information pertains to these waves hidden within Maxwell's equations.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] The electric and magnetic field waves in the far-field travel at the speed of light.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] They have a special restricted orientation and proportional magnitudes, $E_{0}=c_{0}B_{0}$ , which can be seen immediately from the Poynting vector.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] The electric field, magnetic field, and direction of wave propagation are all orthogonal, and the wave propagates in the same direction as $\mathbf {E} \times \mathbf {B}$ .
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] Also **E** and **B** far-fields in free space, which as wave solutions depend primarily on these two Maxwell's equations to remain in phase with each other.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] From the viewpoint of an electromagnetic wave traveling forward, the electric field might be oscillating up and down, while the magnetic field oscillates right and left.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] This picture can be rotated with the electric field oscillating right and left and the magnetic field oscillating down and up.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] This is a different solution that is traveling in the same direction.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] This arbitrariness in the orientation with respect to propagation direction is known as polarization.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] On a quantum level, it is described as photon polarization.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] The direction of the polarization is defined as the direction of the electric field.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] More general forms of the second-order wave equations given above are available, allowing for both non-vacuum propagation media and sources.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] Many competing derivations exist, all with varying levels of approximation and intended applications.
[src:electrodynamics/electromagnetic-radiation-p02] One very general example is a form of the electric field equation, which was factorized into a pair of explicitly directional wave equations, and then efficiently reduced into a single uni-directional wave equation by means of a simple slow-evolution approximation.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] In electrodynamics, the **Larmor formula** is used to calculate the total power radiated by a nonrelativistic point charge as it accelerates.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] It was first derived by Joseph Larmor in 1897, in the context of the wave theory of light.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] When any charged particle (such as an electron, a proton, or an ion) accelerates, energy is radiated in the form of electromagnetic waves.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] A relativistic generalization is given by the Liénard–Wiechert potentials.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] One implication is that an electron orbiting around a nucleus, as in the Bohr model, should lose energy, fall to the nucleus and the atom should collapse.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] This puzzle was not solved until quantum theory was introduced.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] Its nonrelativistic reduction reduces to Larmor's original formula.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] For high-energies, it appears that the power radiated for acceleration parallel to the velocity is a factor $\gamma ^{2}$ larger than that for perpendicular acceleration.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] However, writing the Liénard formula in terms of the velocity gives a misleading implication.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] This shows that the power emitted for $d\mathbf {p} /dt$ perpendicular to the velocity is larger by a factor of $\gamma ^{2}$ than the power for $d\mathbf {p} /dt$ parallel to the velocity.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] This results in radiation damping being negligible for linear accelerators, but a limiting factor for circular accelerators.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] To show this, we reduce the four-vector scalar product to vector notation.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] The angular distribution of radiated power is given by a general formula, applicable whether or not the particle is relativistic.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] In the case of linear motion (velocity parallel to acceleration), this simplifies to ${\frac {dP}{d\Omega }}={\frac {q^{2}a^{2}}{4\pi c^{3}}}{\frac {\sin ^{2}\theta }{{\left(1-\beta \cos \theta \right)}^{5}}},$ where $\theta$ is the angle between the observer and the particle's motion.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] The radiation from a charged particle carries energy and momentum.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] In order to satisfy energy and momentum conservation, the charged particle must experience a recoil at the time of emission.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] The radiation must exert an additional force on the charged particle.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] This force is known as Abraham-Lorentz force while its non-relativistic limit is known as the Lorentz self-force and relativistic forms are known as Lorentz-Dirac force or Abraham-Lorentz-Dirac force.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] The radiation reaction phenomenon is one of the key problems and consequences of the Larmor formula.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] According to classical electrodynamics, a charged particle produces electromagnetic radiation as it accelerates.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] The particle loses momentum and energy as a result of the radiation, which is carrying it away from it.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] The radiation response force, on the other hand, also acts on the charged particle as a result of the radiation.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] The dynamics of charged particles are significantly impacted by the existence of this force.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] In particular, it causes a change in their motion that may be accounted for by the Larmor formula, a factor in the Lorentz-Dirac equation.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] According to the Lorentz-Dirac equation, a charged particle's velocity will be influenced by a "self-force" resulting from its own radiation.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] Such non-physical behavior as runaway solutions, when the particle's velocity or energy become infinite in a finite amount of time, might result from this self-force.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] A resolution to the paradoxes resulting from the introduction of a self-force due to the emission of electromagnetic radiation, is that there is no self-force produced.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] The acceleration of a charged particle produces electromagnetic radiation, whose outgoing energy reduces the energy of the charged particle.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] This results in 'radiation reaction' that decreases the acceleration of the charged particle, not as a self force, but just as less acceleration of the particle.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] The invention of quantum physics, notably the Bohr model of the atom, was able to explain this gap between the classical prediction and the actual reality.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] The Bohr model proposed that transitions between distinct energy levels, which electrons could only inhabit, might account for the observed spectral lines of atoms.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] The wave-like properties of electrons and the idea of energy quantization were used to explain the stability of these electron orbits.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] The Larmor formula can only be used for non-relativistic particles, which limits its usefulness.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] The Liénard-Wiechert potential is a more comprehensive formula that must be employed for particles travelling at relativistic speeds.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] In certain situations, more intricate calculations including numerical techniques or perturbation theory could be necessary to precisely compute the radiation the charged particle emits.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] There is an extension for Larmor formula in special relativity.
[src:electrodynamics/larmor-formula] Lienard-Wiechert formula appears as the restriction of this equation when using a 3-acceleration vector.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] The **Liénard–Wiechert potentials** describe the classical electromagnetic effect of a moving electric point charge in terms of a vector potential and a scalar potential in the Lorenz gauge.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] Stemming directly from Maxwell's equations, these describe the complete, relativistically correct, time-varying electromagnetic field for a point charge in arbitrary motion, but are not corrected for quantum mechanical effects.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] Electromagnetic radiation in the form of waves can be obtained from these potentials.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] These expressions were developed in part by Alfred-Marie Liénard in 1898 and independently by Emil Wiechert in 1900.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] Consider a point charge q exhibiting a prescribed motion along the trajectory $\mathbf {r} _{0}(t)$ with the velocity $\mathbf {v} (t)=d\mathbf {r} _{0}/dt$ .
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] Let $\mathbf {r}$ be the observation point P at time t .
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] The radius vector from the charge q to P is defined as $\mathbf {R} (t)=\mathbf {r} -\mathbf {r} _{0}(t)$ and the distance as $R=|\mathbf {R} |$ .
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] For each value of t , this equation is guaranteed to have only one root for $t_{r}$ , provided the $v=|\mathbf {v} |<c$ .
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] The calculation is nontrivial and requires a number of steps.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] where ${\textstyle {\dot {\mathbf {v} }}=\partial \mathbf {v} /\partial t}$ is the acceleration of the charge q .
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] The magnetic field is orthogonal everywhere to the electric field.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] The first term, depending on the charge velocity and not the acceleration, is linked to the Coulomb-like contribution.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] In other words, it represents the potentials for a uniformly moving charge.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] At large distances, indeed, this contribution to the field decreases like $1/R^{2}$ .
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] The second term, depending on the acceleration, is related to the electromagnetic radiation by the accelerating charge and its contribution to the field decreases like $1/R$ at large distances and therefore dominates the Coulomb-like contribution.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] If the particle acceleration ${\dot {\mathbf {v} }}$ and if this is zero, the charge does not radiate (emit electromagnetic radiation).
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] This term requires additionally that a component of the charge acceleration be in a direction transverse to the line which connects the charge q and the observer of the field $\mathbf {E} (\mathbf {r} ,t)$ .
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] The direction of the field associated with this radiative term is toward the fully time-retarded position of the charge (i.e. where the charge was when it was accelerated).
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] The $\mathbf {R} -{\frac {1}{c}}R\mathbf {v}$ part of the first term of the electric field updates the direction of the field toward the instantaneous position of the charge, if it continues to move with constant velocity $\mathbf {v}$ .
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] This term is connected with the "static" part of the electromagnetic field of the charge.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] On the illustration, we observe an event that happened in the center of the sphere and that propagated at the speed of light.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] The problem is that when the speed of the particle is very close to the speed of light, the particle is then almost on the wave front which explains this strong electrostatic field on the front as we are now very close to the particle.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] Note that outside the propagation sphere, the electric field has its initial state (no connection with the event we observe).
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] When the speed is very close to the speed of light, we consider that the electric field becomes almost flat in the transverse plane, a bit like a "pancake", with an opening angle on $1/\gamma$ .
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] where $\varphi _{0}(\mathbf {r} ,t)$ and $\mathbf {A} _{0}(\mathbf {r} ,t)$ satisfy the homogeneous wave equation with no sources and boundary conditions and they represent external field acting on the system.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] In the case that there are no boundaries surrounding the sources then $\varphi _{0}(\mathbf {r} ,t)=0$ and $\mathbf {A} _{0}(\mathbf {r} ,t)=0$ .
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] where the last equation $F(t_{r})=0$ determines $t_{r}$ .
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] In our case, $t_{r}$ is the retarded time.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] Performing the integration leads to the required Liénard–Wiechert potentials.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] In order to calculate the derivatives of $\varphi$ and $\mathbf {A}$ it is convenient to first compute the derivatives of the retarded time.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] These show that the Lorenz gauge is satisfied, namely that ${\textstyle {\frac {d\varphi }{dt}}+c^{2}{\boldsymbol {\nabla }}\cdot \mathbf {A} =0}$ .
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] The study of classical electrodynamics was instrumental in Albert Einstein's development of the theory of relativity.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] Analysis of the motion and propagation of electromagnetic waves led to the special relativity description of space and time.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] The Liénard–Wiechert formulation is an important launchpad into a deeper analysis of relativistic moving particles.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] The Liénard–Wiechert description is accurate for a large, independently moving particle (i.e. the treatment is "classical" and the acceleration of the charge is due to a force independent of the electromagnetic field).
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] The Liénard–Wiechert formulation always provides two sets of solutions: Advanced fields are absorbed by the charges and retarded fields are emitted.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] Schwarzschild and Fokker considered the advanced field of a system of moving charges, and the retarded field of a system of charges having the same geometry and opposite charges.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] Linearity of Maxwell's equations in vacuum allows one to add both systems, so that the charges disappear: This trick allows Maxwell's equations to become linear in matter.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] To compute energy, it is necessary to use the absolute fields which include the zero point field; otherwise, an error appears, for instance in photon counting.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] It is important to take into account the zero point field discovered by Planck.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] It replaces Einstein's "A" coefficient and explains that the classical electron is stable on Rydberg's classical orbits.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] Moreover, introducing the fluctuations of the zero point field produces Willis E.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] Quantum electrodynamics helped bring together the radiative behavior with the quantum constraints.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] It introduces quantization of normal modes of the electromagnetic field in assumed perfect optical resonators.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] The force on a particle at a given location ***r*** and time *t* depends in a complicated way on the position of the source particles at an earlier time *t*r due to the finite speed, c, at which electromagnetic information travels.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] A particle on Earth 'sees' a charged particle accelerate on the Moon as this acceleration happened 1.5 seconds ago, and a charged particle's acceleration on the Sun as happened 500 seconds ago.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] This earlier time in which an event happens such that a particle at location ***r*** 'sees' this event at a later time *t* is called the retarded time, *tr*.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] The retarded time varies with position; for example the retarded time at the Moon is 1.5 seconds before the current time and the retarded time on the Sun is 500 s before the current time on the Earth.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] where $R(t_{r})$ is the distance of the particle from the source at the retarded time.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] Only electromagnetic wave effects depend fully on the retarded time.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] A novel feature in the Liénard–Wiechert potential is seen in the breakup of its terms into two types of field terms (see below), only one of which depends fully on the retarded time.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] The first of these is the static electric (or magnetic) field term that depends only on the distance to the moving charge, and does not depend on the retarded time at all, if the velocity of the source is constant.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] The other term is dynamic, in that it requires that the moving charge be *accelerating* with a component perpendicular to the line connecting the charge and the observer and does not appear unless the source changes velocity.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] This second term is connected with electromagnetic radiation.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] This term, which corrects for time-retardation delays in the direction of the static field, is required by Lorentz invariance.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] A charge moving with a constant velocity must appear to a distant observer in exactly the same way as a static charge appears to a moving observer, and in the latter case, the direction of the static field must change instantaneously, with no time-delay.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] Thus, static fields (the first term) point exactly at the true instantaneous (non-retarded) position of the charged object if its velocity has not changed over the retarded time delay.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] This is true over any distance separating objects.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] The second term, however, which contains information about the acceleration and other unique behavior of the charge that cannot be removed by changing the Lorentz frame (inertial reference frame of the observer), is fully dependent for direction on the time-retarded position of the source.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] Thus, electromagnetic radiation (described by the second term) always appears to come from the direction of the position of the emitting charge **at the retarded time**.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] Only this second term describes information transfer about the behavior of the charge, which transfer occurs (radiates from the charge) at the speed of light.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] The retarded time is not guaranteed to exist in general.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] For example, if, in a given frame of reference, an electron has just been created, then at this very moment another electron does not yet feel its electromagnetic force at all.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] However, under certain conditions, there always exists a retarded time.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] For example, if the source charge has existed for an unlimited amount of time, during which it has always travelled at a speed not exceeding $v_{M}<c$ , then there exists a valid retarded time $t_{r}$ .
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] This can be seen by considering the function $f(t')=|\mathbf {r} -\mathbf {r} _{s}(t')|-c(t-t')$ .
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] By making $\Delta t$ sufficiently large, this can become negative, *i.e.*, at some point in the past, $f(t')<0$ .
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] By the intermediate value theorem, there exists an intermediate $t_{r}$ with $f(t_{r})=0$ , the defining equation of the retarded time.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] Intuitively, as the source charge moves back in time, the cross section of its light cone at present time expands faster than it can recede, so eventually it must reach the point $\mathbf {r}$ .
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] This is not necessarily true if the source charge's speed is allowed to be arbitrarily close to c , *i.e.*, if for any given speed $v<c$ there was some time in the past when the charge was moving at this speed.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] In this case the cross section of the light cone at present time approaches the point $\mathbf {r}$ as the observer travels back in time but does not necessarily ever reach it.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] For a given point $(\mathbf {r} ,t)$ and trajectory of the point source $\mathbf {r} _{s}(t')$ , there is at most one value of the retarded time $t_{r}$ , *i.e.*, one value $t_{r}$ such that $|\mathbf {r} -\mathbf {r} _{s}(t_{r})|=c(t-t_{r})$ .
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] This can be realized by assuming that there are two retarded times $t_{1}$ and $t_{2}$ , with $t_{1}\leq t_{2}$ .
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] The intuitive interpretation is that one can only ever "see" the point source at one location/time at once unless it travels at least at the speed of light to another location.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] As the source moves forward in time, the cross section of its light cone at present time contracts faster than the source can approach, so it can never intersect the point $\mathbf {r}$ again.
[src:electrodynamics/liénard-wiechert-potential] The conclusion is that, under certain conditions, the retarded time exists and is unique.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] In physics, the **Poynting vector** (or **Umov–Poynting vector**) represents the directional energy flux (the energy transfer per unit area, per unit time) or *power flow* of an electromagnetic field.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] The SI unit of the Poynting vector is the watt per square metre (W/m2); kg/s3 in SI base units.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] It is named after its discoverer John Henry Poynting who first derived it in 1884.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] Nikolay Umov is also credited with formulating the concept.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] Oliver Heaviside also discovered it independently in the more general form that recognises the freedom of adding the curl of an arbitrary vector field to the definition.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] The Poynting vector is used throughout electromagnetics in conjunction with Poynting's theorem, the continuity equation expressing conservation of electromagnetic energy, to calculate the power flow in electromagnetic fields.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] This expression is often called the *Abraham form* and is the most widely used.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] The Poynting vector is usually denoted by **S** or **N**.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] In simple terms, the Poynting vector **S**, *at a point*, gives the magnitude and direction of surface power density that are due to electromagnetic fields *at that point*.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] More rigorously, it is the quantity that must be used to make Poynting's theorem valid.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] Poynting's theorem essentially says that the difference between the electromagnetic energy entering a region and the electromagnetic energy leaving a region must equal the energy converted or dissipated in that region, that is, turned into a different form of energy (often heat).
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] Poynting's theorem is simply a statement of local conservation of energy.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] This frequent condition holds in the following simple example in which the Poynting vector is calculated and seen to be consistent with the usual computation of power in an electric circuit.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] We can find a relatively simple solution in the case of power transmission through a section of coaxial cable analyzed in cylindrical coordinates as depicted in the accompanying diagram.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] The model's symmetry implies that there is no dependence on *θ* (circular symmetry) nor on *Z* (position along the cable).
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] The coaxial cable is specified as having an inner conductor of radius *R*1 and an outer conductor whose inner radius is *R*2 (its thickness beyond *R*2 doesn't affect the following analysis).
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] In between *R*1 and *R*2 the cable contains an ideal dielectric material of relative permittivity *ε*r and we assume conductors that are non-magnetic (so *μ* = *μ*0) and lossless (perfect conductors), all of which are good approximations to real-world coaxial cable in typical situations.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] The central conductor is at voltage *V* and draws a current *I* toward the right, so we expect a total power flow of *P* = *V* · *I* according to basic laws of electricity.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] By evaluating the Poynting vector, however, we are able to identify the profile of power flow in terms of the electric and magnetic fields inside the coaxial cable.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] The magnetic field, again by symmetry, can be non-zero only in the *θ* direction, that is, a vector field looping around the center conductor at every radius between *R*1 and *R*2.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] *Inside* the conductors themselves the magnetic field may or may not be zero, but this is of no concern since the Poynting vector in these regions is zero due to the electric field being zero.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] Outside the entire coaxial cable, the magnetic field is identically zero since paths in this region enclose a net current of zero (+*I* in the center conductor and −*I* in the outer conductor), and again the electric field is zero there anyway.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] Other similar examples in which the *P* = *V* · *I* result can be analytically calculated are: the parallel-plate transmission line, using Cartesian coordinates, and the two-wire transmission line, using bipolar cylindrical coordinates.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] In the "microscopic" version of Maxwell's equations, this definition must be replaced by a definition in terms of the electric field **E** and the magnetic flux density **B** (described later in the article).
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] It is also possible to combine the electric displacement field **D** with the magnetic flux **B** to get the *Minkowski form* of the Poynting vector, or use **D** and **H** to construct yet another version.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] The choice has been controversial: Pfeifer et al. summarize and to a certain extent resolve the century-long dispute between proponents of the Abraham and Minkowski forms (see Abraham–Minkowski controversy).
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] The Poynting vector represents the particular case of an energy flux vector for electromagnetic energy.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] However, any type of energy has its direction of movement in space, as well as its density, so energy flux vectors can be defined for other types of energy as well, e.g., for mechanical energy.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] The Umov–Poynting vector discovered by Nikolay Umov in 1874 describes energy flux in liquid and elastic media in a completely generalized view.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] The first term in the right-hand side represents the electromagnetic energy flow into a small volume, while the second term subtracts the work done by the field on free electrical currents, which thereby exits from electromagnetic energy as dissipation, heat, etc.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] In this definition, bound electrical currents are not included in this term and instead contribute to **S** and *u*.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] Here *ε* and *μ* are scalar, real-valued constants independent of position, direction, and frequency.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] In principle, this limits Poynting's theorem in this form to fields in vacuum and nondispersive linear materials.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] A generalization to dispersive materials is possible under certain circumstances at the cost of additional terms.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] One consequence of the Poynting formula is that for the electromagnetic field to do work, both magnetic and electric fields must be present.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] The magnetic field alone or the electric field alone cannot do any work.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] In a propagating electromagnetic plane wave in an isotropic lossless medium, the instantaneous Poynting vector always points in the direction of propagation while rapidly oscillating in magnitude.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] Since **E** and **H** are at right angles to each other, the magnitude of their cross product is the product of their magnitudes.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] Without loss of generality let us take *X* to be the direction of the electric field and *Y* to be the direction of the magnetic field.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] However, the expression using *E*rms is totally general, applying, for instance, in the case of noise whose RMS amplitude can be measured but where the "peak" amplitude is meaningless.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] In free space the intrinsic impedance *η* is simply given by the impedance of free space *η*0 ≈ 377 Ω.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] In optics, the value of radiated flux crossing a surface, thus the average Poynting vector component in the direction normal to that surface, is technically known as the irradiance, more often simply referred to as the *intensity* (a somewhat ambiguous term).
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] The "microscopic" (differential) version of Maxwell's equations admits only the fundamental fields **E** and **B**, without a built-in model of material media.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] Only the vacuum permittivity and permeability are used, and there is no **D** or **H**.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] This is actually the general expression of the Poynting vector.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] It can be derived directly from Maxwell's equations in terms of *total* charge and current and the Lorentz force law only.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] The two alternative definitions of the Poynting *vector* are equal in vacuum or in non-magnetic materials, where **B** = *μ*0**H**.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] Since only the microscopic fields **E** and **B** occur in the derivation of **S** = (1/*μ*0) **E** × **B** and the energy density, assumptions about any material present are avoided.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] The Poynting vector and theorem and expression for energy density are universally valid in vacuum and all materials.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] The above form for the Poynting vector represents the *instantaneous* power flow due to *instantaneous* electric and magnetic fields.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] More commonly, problems in electromagnetics are solved in terms of sinusoidally varying fields at a specified frequency.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] The results can then be applied more generally, for instance, by representing incoherent radiation as a superposition of such waves at different frequencies and with fluctuating amplitudes.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] We would thus not be considering the instantaneous **E**(*t*) and **H**(*t*) used above, but rather a complex (vector) amplitude for each which describes a coherent wave's phase (as well as amplitude) using phasor notation.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] These complex amplitude vectors are *not* functions of time, as they are understood to refer to oscillations over all time.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] A phasor such as **E**m is understood to signify a sinusoidally varying field whose instantaneous amplitude **E**(*t*) follows the real part of **E**m *ejωt* where ω is the (radian) frequency of the sinusoidal wave being considered.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] In the time domain, it will be seen that the instantaneous power flow will be fluctuating at a frequency of 2*ω*.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] But what is normally of interest is the *average* power flow in which those fluctuations are not considered.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] In the math below, this is accomplished by integrating over a full cycle *T* = 2*π* / *ω*.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] The following quantity, still referred to as a "Poynting vector", is expressed directly in terms of the phasors as: $\mathbf {S} _{\mathrm {m} }={\tfrac {1}{2}}\mathbf {E} _{\mathrm {m} }\times \mathbf {H} _{\mathrm {m} }^{*},$ where ∗ denotes the complex conjugate.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] The time-averaged power flow (according to the instantaneous Poynting vector averaged over a full cycle, for instance) is then given by the *real part* of **S**m.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] The imaginary part is usually ignored, however, it signifies "reactive power" such as the interference due to a standing wave or the near field of an antenna.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] In a single electromagnetic plane wave (rather than a standing wave which can be described as two such waves travelling in opposite directions), **E** and **H** are exactly in phase, so **S**m is simply a real number according to the above definition.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] According to some conventions, the factor of 1/2 in the above definition may be left out.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] Multiplication by 1/2 is required to properly describe the power flow since the magnitudes of **E**m and **H**m refer to the *peak* fields of the oscillating quantities.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] If rather the fields are described in terms of their root mean square (RMS) values (which are each smaller by the factor ${\sqrt {2}}/2$ ), then the correct average power flow is obtained without multiplication by 1/2.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] If a conductor has significant resistance, then, near the surface of that conductor, the Poynting vector would be tilted toward and impinge upon the conductor.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] Once the Poynting vector enters the conductor, it is bent to a direction that is almost perpendicular to the surface.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] This is a consequence of Snell's law and the very slow speed of light inside a conductor.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] The definition and computation of the speed of light in a conductor can be given.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] Inside the conductor, the Poynting vector represents energy flow from the electromagnetic field into the wire, producing resistive Joule heating in the wire.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] For a derivation that starts with Snell's law see Reitz page 454.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] The density of the linear momentum of the electromagnetic field is *S*/*c*2 where *S* is the magnitude of the Poynting vector and *c* is the speed of light in free space.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] The Poynting vector occurs in Poynting's theorem only through its divergence ∇ ⋅ **S**, that is, it is only required that the surface integral of the Poynting vector around a closed surface describe the net flow of electromagnetic energy into or out of the enclosed volume.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] This means that adding a solenoidal vector field (one with zero divergence) to **S** will result in another field that satisfies this required property of a Poynting vector field according to Poynting's theorem.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] Since the divergence of any curl is zero, one can add the curl of any vector field to the Poynting vector and the resulting vector field **S**′ will still satisfy Poynting's theorem.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] However even though the Poynting vector was originally formulated only for the sake of Poynting's theorem in which only its divergence appears, it turns out that the above choice of its form *is* unique.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] The following section gives an example which illustrates why it is *not* acceptable to add an arbitrary solenoidal field to **E** × **H**.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] The consideration of the Poynting vector in static fields shows the relativistic nature of the Maxwell equations and allows a better understanding of the magnetic component of the Lorentz force, *q*(**v** × **B**).
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] To illustrate, the accompanying picture is considered, which describes the Poynting vector in a cylindrical capacitor, which is located in an **H** field (pointing into the page) generated by a permanent magnet.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] Although there are only static electric and magnetic fields, the calculation of the Poynting vector produces a clockwise circular flow of electromagnetic energy, with no beginning or end.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] While the circulating energy flow may seem unphysical, its existence is necessary to maintain conservation of angular momentum.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] The momentum of an electromagnetic wave in free space is equal to its power divided by *c*, the speed of light.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] Therefore, the circular flow of electromagnetic energy implies an *angular* momentum.
[src:electrodynamics/poynting-vector] That angular momentum would match the "hidden" angular momentum, revealed by the Poynting vector, circulating before the capacitor was discharged.
[src:electrodynamics/retarded-potential] In electrodynamics, the **retarded potentials** are the electromagnetic potentials for the electromagnetic field generated by time-varying electric current or charge distributions in the past.
[src:electrodynamics/retarded-potential] where φ(**r**, *t*) is the electric potential and **A**(**r**, *t*) is the magnetic vector potential, for an arbitrary source of charge density ρ(**r**, *t*) and current density **J**(**r**, *t*), and $\Box$ is the D'Alembert operator.
[src:electrodynamics/retarded-potential] Solving these gives the retarded potentials below (all in SI units).
[src:electrodynamics/retarded-potential] is the retarded time, and d3**r'** is the integration measure using **r'**.
[src:electrodynamics/retarded-potential] and this leads to Jefimenko's equations.
[src:electrodynamics/retarded-potential] These also follow directly from the retarded potentials.
[src:electrodynamics/retarded-potential] This presents an advantage and a disadvantage of the Coulomb gauge - φ is easily calculable from the charge distribution ρ but **A** is not so easily calculable from the current distribution **j**.
[src:electrodynamics/retarded-potential] The retarded potential in linearized general relativity is closely analogous to the electromagnetic case.
[src:electrodynamics/retarded-potential] A many-body theory which includes an average of retarded and *advanced* Liénard–Wiechert potentials is the Wheeler–Feynman absorber theory also known as the Wheeler–Feynman time-symmetric theory.
[src:electrodynamics/retarded-potential] In gravitation, there are application examples for calculating deviations in orbits of satellites, moons or planets.
[src:electrodynamics/retarded-potential] The anomalies in the rotation curves of more than one hundred spiral galaxies of different types could also be explained.
[src:electrodynamics/retarded-potential] The data of the “SPARC (Spitzer Photometry and Accurate Rotation Curves) Galaxy collection”, which were recorded with the Spitzer Space Telescope, were used for this purpose.
[src:electrodynamics/retarded-potential] In this way, neither the assumption of dark matter nor a modification of general relativity is required to explain the observations.
[src:electrodynamics/retarded-potential] The potential of charge with uniform speed on a straight line has inversion in a point that is in the recent position.
[src:electrodynamics/retarded-potential] The potential is not changed in the direction of movement.
